Text: NIXON: Good evening, Mr. Howe.
Speech: Good evening, Mr. Howe.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: KENNEDY: Good evening, Mr. Howe.
Speech: Good evening, Mr. Howe.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: NIXON: Mr. Howe, Senator Kennedy, my fellow Americans.
Speech: Mr. Howe, Senator Kennedy, my fellow Americans.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: Since this campaign began I have had a very rare privilege.
Speech: Since this campaign began I have had a very rare privilege.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: I have traveled to forty-eight of the fifty states and in my travels I have learned what the people of the United States are thinking about.
Speech: I have traveled to forty-eight of the fifty states and in my travels I have learned what the people of the United States are thinking about.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: There is one issue that stands out above all the rest, one in which every American is concerned, regardless of what group he may be a member and regardless of where he may live.
Speech: There is one issue that stands out above all the rest, one in which every American is concerned, regardless of what group he may be a member and regardless of where he may live.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: And that issue, very simply stated, is this: how can we keep the peace - keep it without surrender?
Speech: And that issue, very simply stated, is this: how can we keep the peace - keep it without surrender?
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: How can we extend freedom - extend it without war?
Speech: How can we extend freedom - extend it without war?
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: Now in determining how we deal with this issue, we must find the answer to a very important but simple question: who threatens the peace?
Speech: Now in determining how we deal with this issue, we must find the answer to a very important but simple question: who threatens the peace?
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: Who threatens freedom in the world?
Speech: Who threatens freedom in the world?
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: There is only one threat to peace and one threat to freedom - that that is presented by the international Communist movement.
Speech: There is only one threat to peace and one threat to freedom - that that is presented by the international Communist movement.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: And therefore if we are to have peace, we must know how to deal with the Communists and their leaders.
Speech: And therefore if we are to have peace, we must know how to deal with the Communists and their leaders.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: I know Mr. Khrushchev.
Speech: I know Mr. Khrushchev.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: I also have had the opportunity of knowing and meeting other Communist leaders in the world.
Speech: I also have had the opportunity of knowing and meeting other Communist leaders in the world.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: I believe there are certain principles we must find in dealing with him and his colleagues - principles, if followed, that will keep the peace and that also can extend freedom.
Speech: I believe there are certain principles we must find in dealing with him and his colleagues - principles, if followed, that will keep the peace and that also can extend freedom.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: First, we have to learn from the past, because we cannot afford to make the mistakes of the past.
Speech: First, we have to learn from the past, because we cannot afford to make the mistakes of the past.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: In the seven years before this Administration came into power in Washington, we found that six hundred million people went behind the Iron Curtain.
Speech: In the seven years before this Administration came into power in Washington, we found that six hundred million people went behind the Iron Curtain.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: And at the end of that seven years we were engaged in a war in Korea which cost of thirty thousand American lives.
Speech: And at the end of that seven years we were engaged in a war in Korea which cost of thirty thousand American lives.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: In the past seven years, in President Eisenhower's Administration, this situation has been reversed.
Speech: In the past seven years, in President Eisenhower's Administration, this situation has been reversed.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: We ended the Korean War; by strong, firm leadership we have kept out of other wars; and we have avoided surrender of principle or territory at the conference table.
Speech: We ended the Korean War; by strong, firm leadership we have kept out of other wars; and we have avoided surrender of principle or territory at the conference table.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: Now why were we successful, as our predecessors were not successful?
Speech: Now why were we successful, as our predecessors were not successful?
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: I think there're several reasons.
Speech: I think there're several reasons.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: In the first place, they made a fatal error in misjudging the Communists; in trying to apply to them the same rules of conduct that you would apply to the leaders of the free world.
Speech: In the first place, they made a fatal error in misjudging the Communists; in trying to apply to them the same rules of conduct that you would apply to the leaders of the free world.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: One of the major errors they made was the one that led to the Korean War.
Speech: One of the major errors they made was the one that led to the Korean War.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: In ruling out the defense of Korea, they invited aggression in that area.
Speech: In ruling out the defense of Korea, they invited aggression in that area.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: They thought they were going to have peace - it brought war.
Speech: They thought they were going to have peace - it brought war.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: We learned from their mistakes.
Speech: We learned from their mistakes.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: And so, in our seven years, we find that we have been firm in our diplomacy; we have never made concessions without getting concessions in return.
Speech: And so, in our seven years, we find that we have been firm in our diplomacy; we have never made concessions without getting concessions in return.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: We have always been willing to go the extra mile to negotiate for disarmament or in any other area.
Speech: We have always been willing to go the extra mile to negotiate for disarmament or in any other area.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: But we have never been willing to do anything that, in effect, surrendered freedom any place in the world.
Speech: But we have never been willing to do anything that, in effect, surrendered freedom any place in the world.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: That is why President Eisenhower was correct in not apologizing or expressing regrets to Mr. Khrushchev at the Paris Conference, as Senator Kennedy suggested he could have done.
Speech: That is why President Eisenhower was correct in not apologizing or expressing regrets to Mr. Khrushchev at the Paris Conference, as Senator Kennedy suggested he could have done.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: That is why Senator wh- President Eisenhower was also correct in his policy in the Formosa Straits, where he declined, and refused to follow the recommendations - recommendations which Senator Kennedy voted for in 1955; again made in 1959; again repeated in his debates that you have heard - recommendations with regard to - again - slicing off a piece of free territory, and abandoning it, if - in effect, to the Communists.
Speech: That is why Senator wh- President Eisenhower was also correct in his policy in the Formosa Straits, where he declined, and refused to follow the recommendations - recommendations which Senator Kennedy voted for in 1955; again made in 1959; again repeated in his debates that you have heard - recommendations with regard to - again - slicing off a piece of free territory, and abandoning it, if - in effect, to the Communists.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: Why did the President feel this was wrong and why was the President right and his critics wrong?
Speech: Why did the President feel this was wrong and why was the President right and his critics wrong?
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: Because again this showed a lack of understanding of dictators, a lack of understanding particularly of Communists, because every time you make such a concession it does not lead to peace; it only encourages them to blackmail you.
Speech: Because again this showed a lack of understanding of dictators, a lack of understanding particularly of Communists, because every time you make such a concession it does not lead to peace; it only encourages them to blackmail you.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: It encourages them to begin a war.
Speech: It encourages them to begin a war.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: And so I say that the record shows that we know how to keep the peace, to keep it without surrender.
Speech: And so I say that the record shows that we know how to keep the peace, to keep it without surrender.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: Let us move now to the future.
Speech: Let us move now to the future.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: It is not enough to stand on this record because we are dealing with the most ruthless, fanatical... leaders that the world has ever seen.
Speech: It is not enough to stand on this record because we are dealing with the most ruthless, fanatical... leaders that the world has ever seen.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: That is why I say that in this period of the sixties, America must move forward in every area.
Speech: That is why I say that in this period of the sixties, America must move forward in every area.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: First of all, although we are today, as Senator Kennedy has admitted, the strongest nation in the world militarily, we must increase our strength, increase it so that we will always have enough strength that regardless of what our potential opponents have - if the should launch a surprise attack - we will be able to destroy their war-making capability.
Speech: First of all, although we are today, as Senator Kennedy has admitted, the strongest nation in the world militarily, we must increase our strength, increase it so that we will always have enough strength that regardless of what our potential opponents have - if the should launch a surprise attack - we will be able to destroy their war-making capability.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: They must know, in other words, that it is national suicide if they begin anything.
Speech: They must know, in other words, that it is national suicide if they begin anything.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: We need this kind of strength because we're the guardians of the peace.
Speech: We need this kind of strength because we're the guardians of the peace.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: In addition to military strength, we need to see that the economy of this country continues to grow.
Speech: In addition to military strength, we need to see that the economy of this country continues to grow.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: It has grown in the past seven years.
Speech: It has grown in the past seven years.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: It can and will grow even more in the next four.
Speech: It can and will grow even more in the next four.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: And the reason that it must grow even more is because we have things to do at home and also because we're in a race for survival - a race in which it isn't enough to be ahead; it isn't enough simply to be complacent.
Speech: And the reason that it must grow even more is because we have things to do at home and also because we're in a race for survival - a race in which it isn't enough to be ahead; it isn't enough simply to be complacent.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: We have to move ahead in order to stay ahead.
Speech: We have to move ahead in order to stay ahead.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: And that is why, in this field, I have made recommendations which I am confident will move the American economy ahead - move it firmly and soundly so that there will never be a time when the Soviet Union will be able to challenge our superiority in this field.
Speech: And that is why, in this field, I have made recommendations which I am confident will move the American economy ahead - move it firmly and soundly so that there will never be a time when the Soviet Union will be able to challenge our superiority in this field.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: And so we need military strength, we need economic strength, we also need the right diplomatic policies.
Speech: And so we need military strength, we need economic strength, we also need the right diplomatic policies.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: What are they?
Speech: What are they?
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: Again we turn to the past.
Speech: Again we turn to the past.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: Firmness but no belligerence, and by no belligerence I mean that we do not answer insult by insult.
Speech: Firmness but no belligerence, and by no belligerence I mean that we do not answer insult by insult.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: When you are proud and confident of your strength, you do not get down to the level of Mr. Khrushchev and his colleagues.
Speech: When you are proud and confident of your strength, you do not get down to the level of Mr. Khrushchev and his colleagues.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: And that example that President Eisenhower has set we will continue to follow.
Speech: And that example that President Eisenhower has set we will continue to follow.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: But all this by itself is not enough.
Speech: But all this by itself is not enough.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: It is not enough for us simply to be the strongest nation militarily, the strongest economically, and also to have firm diplomacy.
Speech: It is not enough for us simply to be the strongest nation militarily, the strongest economically, and also to have firm diplomacy.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: We must have a great goal.
Speech: We must have a great goal.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: And that is: not just to keep freedom for ourselves but to extend it to all the world, to extend it to all the world because that is America's destiny.
Speech: not just to keep freedom for ourselves but to extend it to all the world, to extend it to all the world because that is America's destiny.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: To extend it to all the world because the Communist aim is not to hold their own but to extend Communism.
Speech: To extend it to all the world because the Communist aim is not to hold their own but to extend Communism.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: And you cannot fight a victory for Communism or a strategy of victory for Communism with the strategy, simply of holding the line.
Speech: And you cannot fight a victory for Communism or a strategy of victory for Communism with the strategy, simply of holding the line.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: And so I say that we believe that our policies of military strength, of economic strength, of diplomatic firmness first will keep the peace and keep it without surrender.
Speech: And so I say that we believe that our policies of military strength, of economic strength, of diplomatic firmness first will keep the peace and keep it without surrender.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: We also believe that in the great field of ideals that we can lead America to the victory for freedom - victory in the newly developing countries, victory also in the captive countries - provided we have faith in ourselves and faith in our principles.
Speech: We also believe that in the great field of ideals that we can lead America to the victory for freedom - victory in the newly developing countries, victory also in the captive countries - provided we have faith in ourselves and faith in our principles.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: KENNEDY: Mr. Howe, Mr. Vice President.
Speech: Mr. Howe, Mr. Vice President.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: First uh - let me again try to correct the record on the matter of Quemoy and Matsu.
Speech: First uh - let me again try to correct the record on the matter of Quemoy and Matsu.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: I voted for the Formosa resolution in 1955.
Speech: I voted for the Formosa resolution in 1955.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: I have sustained it since then.
Speech: I have sustained it since then.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: I've said that I agree with the Administration policy.
Speech: I've said that I agree with the Administration policy.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: Mr. Nixon earlier indicated that he would defend Quemoy and Matsu even if the attack on these islands, two miles off the coast of China, were not part of a general attack an Formosa and the Pescadores.
Speech: Mr. Nixon earlier indicated that he would defend Quemoy and Matsu even if the attack on these islands, two miles off the coast of China, were not part of a general attack an Formosa and the Pescadores.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: I indicated that I would defend those islands if the attack were directed against Pescadores and Formosa, which is part of the Eisenhower policy.
Speech: I indicated that I would defend those islands if the attack were directed against Pescadores and Formosa, which is part of the Eisenhower policy.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: I've supported that policy.
Speech: I've supported that policy.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: In the last week, as a member of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, I have re-read the testimony of General Twining representing the Administration in 1959, and the Assistant Secretary of State before the Foreign Relations Committee in 1958, and I have accurately described the Administration policy, and I support it wholeheartedly.
Speech: In the last week, as a member of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, I have re-read the testimony of General Twining representing the Administration in 1959, and the Assistant Secretary of State before the Foreign Relations Committee in 1958, and I have accurately described the Administration policy, and I support it wholeheartedly.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: So that really isn't an issue in this campaign.
Speech: So that really isn't an issue in this campaign.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: It isn't an issue with Mr. Nixon, who now says that he also supports the Eisenhower policy.
Speech: It isn't an issue with Mr. Nixon, who now says that he also supports the Eisenhower policy.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: Nor is the question that all Americans want peace and security an issue in this campaign.
Speech: Nor is the question that all Americans want peace and security an issue in this campaign.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: The question is: are we moving in the direction of peace and security?
Speech: are we moving in the direction of peace and security?
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: Is our relative strength growing?
Speech: Is our relative strength growing?
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: Is, as Mr. Nixon says, our prestige at an all-time high, as he said a week ago, and that of the Communists at an all-time low?
Speech: Is, as Mr. Nixon says, our prestige at an all-time high, as he said a week ago, and that of the Communists at an all-time low?
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: I don't believe it is.
Speech: I don't believe it is.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: I don't believe that our relative strength is increasing.
Speech: I don't believe that our relative strength is increasing.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: And I say that not as the Democratic standard-bearer, but as a citizen of the United States who is concerned about the United States.
Speech: And I say that not as the Democratic standard-bearer, but as a citizen of the United States who is concerned about the United States.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: I look at Cuba, ninety miles off the coast of the United States.
Speech: I look at Cuba, ninety miles off the coast of the United States.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: In 1957 I was in Havana.
Speech: In 1957 I was in Havana.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: I talked to the American Ambassador there.
Speech: I talked to the American Ambassador there.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: He said that he was the second most powerful man in Cuba.
Speech: He said that he was the second most powerful man in Cuba.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: And yet even though Ambassador Smith and Ambassador Gardner, both Republican Ambassadors, both warned of Castro, the Marxist influences around Castro, the Communist influences around Castro, both of them have testified in the last six weeks, that in spite of their warnings to the American government, nothing was done.
Speech: And yet even though Ambassador Smith and Ambassador Gardner, both Republican Ambassadors, both warned of Castro, the Marxist influences around Castro, the Communist influences around Castro, both of them have testified in the last six weeks, that in spite of their warnings to the American government, nothing was done.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: Our d- security depends upon Latin America.
Speech: Our d- security depends upon Latin America.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: Can any American looking at the situation in Latin America feel contented with what's happening today, when a candidate for the presidency of Brazil feels it necessary to call - not on Washington during the campaign - but on Castro in Havana, in order to pick up the support of the Castro supporters in Brazil?
Speech: Can any American looking at the situation in Latin America feel contented with what's happening today, when a candidate for the presidency of Brazil feels it necessary to call - not on Washington during the campaign - but on Castro in Havana, in order to pick up the support of the Castro supporters in Brazil?
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: At the American Conference - Inter-American Conference this summer, when we wanted them to join together in the denunciation of Castro and the Cuban Communists, we couldn't even get the Inter-American group to join together in denouncing Castro.
Speech: At the American Conference - Inter-American Conference this summer, when we wanted them to join together in the denunciation of Castro and the Cuban Communists, we couldn't even get the Inter-American group to join together in denouncing Castro.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: It was rather a vague statement that they finally made.
Speech: It was rather a vague statement that they finally made.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: Do you know today that the Com- the Russians broadcast ten times as many programs in Spanish to Latin America as we do?
Speech: Do you know today that the Com- the Russians broadcast ten times as many programs in Spanish to Latin America as we do?
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: Do you know we don't have a single program sponsored by our government to Cuba - to tell them our story, to tell them that we are their friends, that we want them to be free again?
Speech: Do you know we don't have a single program sponsored by our government to Cuba - to tell them our story, to tell them that we are their friends, that we want them to be free again?
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: Africa is now the emerging area of the world.
Speech: Africa is now the emerging area of the world.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: It contains twenty-five percent of all the members of the General Assembly.
Speech: It contains twenty-five percent of all the members of the General Assembly.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: We didn't even have a Bureau of African Affairs until 1957.
Speech: We didn't even have a Bureau of African Affairs until 1957.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: In the Africa south of the Sahara, which is the major new section, we have less students from all of Africa in that area studying under government auspices today than from the country of Thailand.
Speech: In the Africa south of the Sahara, which is the major new section, we have less students from all of Africa in that area studying under government auspices today than from the country of Thailand.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: If there's one thing Africa needs it's technical assistance.
Speech: If there's one thing Africa needs it's technical assistance.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: And yet last year we gave them less than five percent of all the technical assistance funds that we distributed around the world.
Speech: And yet last year we gave them less than five percent of all the technical assistance funds that we distributed around the world.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: We relied in the Middle East on the Baghdad Pact, and yet when the Iraqi Government was changed, the Baghdad Pact broke down.
Speech: We relied in the Middle East on the Baghdad Pact, and yet when the Iraqi Government was changed, the Baghdad Pact broke down.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: We relied on the Eisenhower Doctrine for the Middle East, which passed the Senate.
Speech: We relied on the Eisenhower Doctrine for the Middle East, which passed the Senate.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: There isn't one country in the Middle East that now endorses the Eisenhower Doctrine.
Speech: There isn't one country in the Middle East that now endorses the Eisenhower Doctrine.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: We look to Europe uh - to Asia because the struggle is in the underdeveloped world.
Speech: We look to Europe uh - to Asia because the struggle is in the underdeveloped world.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: Which system, Communism or freedom, will triumph in the next five or ten years?
Speech: Which system, Communism or freedom, will triumph in the next five or ten years?
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: That's what should concern us, not the history of ten, or fifteen, or twenty years ago.
Speech: That's what should concern us, not the history of ten, or fifteen, or twenty years ago.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: But are we doing enough in these areas?
Speech: But are we doing enough in these areas?
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: What are freedom's chances in those areas?
Speech: What are freedom's chances in those areas?
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: By 1965 or 1970, will there be other Cubas in Latin America?
Speech: By 1965 or 1970, will there be other Cubas in Latin America?
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: Will Guinea and Ghana, which have now voted with the Communists frequently as newly independent countries of Africa - will there be others?
Speech: Will Guinea and Ghana, which have now voted with the Communists frequently as newly independent countries of Africa - will there be others?
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: Will the Congo go Communist?
Speech: Will the Congo go Communist?
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: Will other countries?
Speech: Will other countries?
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: Are we doing enough in that area?
Speech: Are we doing enough in that area?
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: And what about Asia?
Speech: And what about Asia?
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: Is India going to win the economic struggle or is China going to win it?
Speech: Is India going to win the economic struggle or is China going to win it?
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: Who will dominate Asia in the next five or ten years?
Speech: Who will dominate Asia in the next five or ten years?
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: Communism?
Speech: Communism?
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: The Chinese?
Speech: The Chinese?
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: Or will freedom?
Speech: Or will freedom?
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: The question which we have to decide as Americans - are we doing enough today?
Speech: The question which we have to decide as Americans - are we doing enough today?
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: Is our strength and prestige rising?
Speech: Is our strength and prestige rising?
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: Do people want to be identified with us?
Speech: Do people want to be identified with us?
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: Do they want to follow United States leadership?
Speech: Do they want to follow United States leadership?
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: I don't think they do, enough.
Speech: I don't think they do, enough.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: And that's what concerns me.
Speech: And that's what concerns me.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: In Africa - these countries that have newly joined the United Nations.
Speech: In Africa - these countries that have newly joined the United Nations.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Speech: More countries in Asia voted against us on that question than voted with us.

Name: John F. Kennedy

Speech: I believe that this struggle is going to go on, and it may be well decided in the next decade.

Name: John F. Kennedy

Name: John F. Kennedy

Speech: There are six countries in Africa that are members of the United Nations.

Name: John F. Kennedy

Speech: When Guinea became independent, the Soviet Ambassador showed up that very day.

Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: I believe that the world is changing fast.
Speech: I believe that the world is changing fast.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: And I don't think this Administration has shown the foresight, has shown the knowledge, has been identified with the great fight which these people are waging to be free, to get a better standard of living, to live better.
Speech: And I don't think this Administration has shown the foresight, has shown the knowledge, has been identified with the great fight which these people are waging to be free, to get a better standard of living, to live better.

Name: John F. Kennedy

Name: John F. Kennedy

Speech: And we've been in - on the whole, uninterested.

Name: John F. Kennedy

Speech: I think we're going to have to do better.

Name: John F. Kennedy

Speech: Mr. Nixon talks about our being the strongest country in the world.

Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: I think we are today.
Speech: I think we are today.

Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: But we were far stronger relative to the Communists five years ago, and what is of great concern is that the balance of power is in danger of moving with them.
Speech: But we were far stronger relative to the Communists five years ago, and what is of great concern is that the balance of power is in danger of moving with them.

Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: They made a breakthrough in missiles, and by nineteen sixty-one, two, and three, they will be outnumbering us in missiles.
Speech: They made a breakthrough in missiles, and by nineteen sixty-one, two, and three, they will be outnumbering us in missiles.

Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: I'm not as confident as he is that we will be the strongest military power by 1963.
Speech: I'm not as confident as he is that we will be the strongest military power by 1963.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: He talks about economic growth as a great indicator of freedom.
Speech: He talks about economic growth as a great indicator of freedom.

Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: I agree with him.
Speech: I agree with him.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: What we do in this country, the kind of society that we build, that will tell whether freedom will be sustained around the world.
Speech: What we do in this country, the kind of society that we build, that will tell whether freedom will be sustained around the world.

Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: And yet, in the last nine months of this year, we've had a drop in our economic growth rather than a gain.
Speech: And yet, in the last nine months of this year, we've had a drop in our economic growth rather than a gain.

Name: John F. Kennedy

Speech: We've had the lowest rate of increase of economic growth in the last nine months of any major industrialized society in the world.

Name: John F. Kennedy

Speech: I look up and see the Soviet flag on the moon.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Speech: The fact is that the State Department polls on our prestige and influence around the world have shown such a sharp drop that up till now the State Department has been unwilling to release them.

Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: And yet they were polled by the U.S.I.A.
Speech: And yet they were polled by the U.S.I.A.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: The point of all this is, this is a struggle in which we're engaged.
Speech: The point of all this is, this is a struggle in which we're engaged.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: We want peace.
Speech: We want peace.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: We want freedom.
Speech: We want freedom.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: We want security.
Speech: We want security.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: We want to be stronger.
Speech: We want to be stronger.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: We want freedom to gain.
Speech: We want freedom to gain.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: But I don't believe in these changing and revolutionary times this Administration has known that the world is changing - has identified itself with that change.
Speech: But I don't believe in these changing and revolutionary times this Administration has known that the world is changing - has identified itself with that change.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: I think the Communists have been moving with vigor - Laos, Africa, Cuba - all around the world today they're on the move.
Speech: I think the Communists have been moving with vigor - Laos, Africa, Cuba - all around the world today they're on the move.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: I think we have to revita1ize our society.
Speech: I think we have to revita1ize our society.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: I think we have to demonstrate to the people of the world that we're determined in this free country of ours to be first - not first if, and not first but, and not first when - but first.
Speech: I think we have to demonstrate to the people of the world that we're determined in this free country of ours to be first - not first if, and not first but, and not first when - but first.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: And when we are strong and when we are first, then freedom gains; then the prospects for peace increase; then the prospects for our society gain.
Speech: And when we are strong and when we are first, then freedom gains; then the prospects for peace increase; then the prospects for our society gain.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Speech: Our policies are very different.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: I think that Senator Kennedy's policies and recommendations for the handling of the Castro regime are probably the most dangers- dangerously irresponsible recommendations that he's made during the course of this campaign.
Speech: I think that Senator Kennedy's policies and recommendations for the handling of the Castro regime are probably the most dangers- dangerously irresponsible recommendations that he's made during the course of this campaign.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: In effect, what Senator Kennedy recommends is that the United States government should give help to the exiles and to those within Cuba who oppose the Castro regime - provided they are anti-Batista.
Speech: In effect, what Senator Kennedy recommends is that the United States government should give help to the exiles and to those within Cuba who oppose the Castro regime - provided they are anti-Batista.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: Now let's just see what this means.
Speech: Now let's just see what this means.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: We have five treaties with Latin America, including the one setting up the Organization of American States in Bogota in 1948, in which we have agreed not to intervene in the internal affairs of any other American country - and they as well have agreed to do likewise.
Speech: We have five treaties with Latin America, including the one setting up the Organization of American States in Bogota in 1948, in which we have agreed not to intervene in the internal affairs of any other American country - and they as well have agreed to do likewise.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: The charter of the United Nations - its Preamble, Article I and Article II - also provide that there shall be no intervention by one nation in the internal affairs of another.
Speech: The charter of the United Nations - its Preamble, Article I and Article II - also provide that there shall be no intervention by one nation in the internal affairs of another.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: Now I don't know what Senator Kennedy suggests when he says that we should help those who oppose the Castro regime, both in Cuba and without.
Speech: Now I don't know what Senator Kennedy suggests when he says that we should help those who oppose the Castro regime, both in Cuba and without.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: But I do know this: that if we were to follow that recommendation, that we would lose all of our friends in Latin America, we would probably be condemned in the United Nations, and we would not accomplish our objective.
Speech: that if we were to follow that recommendation, that we would lose all of our friends in Latin America, we would probably be condemned in the United Nations, and we would not accomplish our objective.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: I know something else.
Speech: I know something else.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: It would be an open invitation for Mr. Khrushchev to come in, to come into Latin America and to engage us in what would be a civil war, and possibly even worse than that.
Speech: It would be an open invitation for Mr. Khrushchev to come in, to come into Latin America and to engage us in what would be a civil war, and possibly even worse than that.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Speech: This is the major recommendation that he's made.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: Now, what can we do?
Speech: Now, what can we do?
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: Well, we can do what we did with Guatemala.
Speech: Well, we can do what we did with Guatemala.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Speech: There was a Communist dictator that we inherited from the previous Administration.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: We quarantined Mr. Arbenz.
Speech: We quarantined Mr. Arbenz.

Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: The result was that the Guatemalan people themselves eventually rose up and they threw him out.
Speech: The result was that the Guatemalan people themselves eventually rose up and they threw him out.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: We are quarantining Mr. Castro today.
Speech: We are quarantining Mr. Castro today.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: We're quarantining him diplomatically by bringing back our Ambassador; economically by cutting off trade, and Senator Kennedy's suggestion that the trade that we cut off is not significant is just one hundred percent wrong.
Speech: We're quarantining him diplomatically by bringing back our Ambassador; economically by cutting off trade, and Senator Kennedy's suggestion that the trade that we cut off is not significant is just one hundred percent wrong.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: We are cutting off the significant items that the Cuban regime needs in order to survive.
Speech: We are cutting off the significant items that the Cuban regime needs in order to survive.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: By cutting off trade, by cutting off our diplomatic relations as we have, we will quarantine this regime so that the people of Cuba themselves will take care of Mr. Castro.
Speech: By cutting off trade, by cutting off our diplomatic relations as we have, we will quarantine this regime so that the people of Cuba themselves will take care of Mr. Castro.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: But for us to do what Senator Kennedy has suggested would bring results which I know he would not want, and certainly which the American people would not want.
Speech: But for us to do what Senator Kennedy has suggested would bring results which I know he would not want, and certainly which the American people would not want.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: KENNEDY: Mr. Nixon uh - shows himself i- misinformed.
Speech: Mr. Nixon uh - shows himself i- misinformed.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: He surely must be aware that most of the equipment and arms and resources for Castro came from the United States, flowed out of Florida and other parts of the United States to Castro in the mountains.
Speech: He surely must be aware that most of the equipment and arms and resources for Castro came from the United States, flowed out of Florida and other parts of the United States to Castro in the mountains.

Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: There isn't any doubt about that, number one.
Speech: There isn't any doubt about that, number one.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: Number two, I believe that if any economic sanctions against Latin America are going to be successful they have to be multilateral.
Speech: Number two, I believe that if any economic sanctions against Latin America are going to be successful they have to be multilateral.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: They have to include the other countries of Latin America.
Speech: They have to include the other countries of Latin America.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: The very minute effect of the action which has been taken this week on Cuba's economy - I believe Castro can replace those markets very easily through Latin America, through Europe, and through Eastern Europe.
Speech: The very minute effect of the action which has been taken this week on Cuba's economy - I believe Castro can replace those markets very easily through Latin America, through Europe, and through Eastern Europe.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: If the United States had stronger prestige and influence in Latin America it could persuade - as Franklin Roosevelt did in 1940 - the countries of Latin America to join in an economic quarantine of Castro.
Speech: If the United States had stronger prestige and influence in Latin America it could persuade - as Franklin Roosevelt did in 1940 - the countries of Latin America to join in an economic quarantine of Castro.

Name: John F. Kennedy

Speech: That's the only way you can bring real economic pressure on the Castro regime - and also the countries of Western Europe, Canada, Japan and the others.

Name: John F. Kennedy

Speech: Number three, Castro is only the beginning of our difficulties throughout Latin America.

Name: John F. Kennedy

Speech: The big struggle will be to prevent the influence of Castro spreading to other countries - Mexico, Panama, Bolivia, Colombia.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: We're going to have to try to provide closer ties, to associate ourselves with the great desire of these people for a better life if we're going to prevent Castro's influence from spreading throughout all of Latin America.
Speech: We're going to have to try to provide closer ties, to associate ourselves with the great desire of these people for a better life if we're going to prevent Castro's influence from spreading throughout all of Latin America.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: His influence is strong enough today to prevent us from joi- getting the other countries of Latin America to join with us in economic quarantine.
Speech: His influence is strong enough today to prevent us from joi- getting the other countries of Latin America to join with us in economic quarantine.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Speech: His influence is growing - mostly because this Administration has ignored Latin America.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: You yourself said, Mr. Vice President, a month ago, that if we had provided the kind of economic aid five years ago that we are now providing we might never have had Castro.
Speech: You yourself said, Mr. Vice President, a month ago, that if we had provided the kind of economic aid five years ago that we are now providing we might never have had Castro.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: Why didn't we?
Speech: Why didn't we?
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: KENNEDY: Mr. Edwards, I don't think it's a wise idea for presidential candidates to appoint the members of his cabinet prospectively, or to suggest four people - indicate that one of them surely will be appointed.
Speech: Mr. Edwards, I don't think it's a wise idea for presidential candidates to appoint the members of his cabinet prospectively, or to suggest four people - indicate that one of them surely will be appointed.

Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: This is a decision that the president of the United States must make.
Speech: This is a decision that the president of the United States must make.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy
