Speech: The last candidate who indicated that he knew who his cabinet was going to be was Mr. Dewey in 1948.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: This is a race between the Vice President and myself for the presidency of the United States.
Speech: This is a race between the Vice President and myself for the presidency of the United States.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: There are a good many able men who could be secretary of state.
Speech: There are a good many able men who could be secretary of state.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: I've made no judgment about who should be secretary of state.
Speech: I've made no judgment about who should be secretary of state.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: I think that judgment could be made after election, if I'm successful.
Speech: I think that judgment could be made after election, if I'm successful.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: The people have to make a choice between Mr. Nixon and myself, between the Republican party and the Democratic party, between our approach to the problems which now disturb us as a nation and disturb us as a world power.
Speech: The people have to make a choice between Mr. Nixon and myself, between the Republican party and the Democratic party, between our approach to the problems which now disturb us as a nation and disturb us as a world power.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: The president bears the constitutional responsibility, not the secretary of state, for the conduct of foreign affairs.
Speech: The president bears the constitutional responsibility, not the secretary of state, for the conduct of foreign affairs.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: Some presidents have been strong in foreign policy; others have relied heavily on the secretary of state.
Speech: Some presidents have been strong in foreign policy; others have relied heavily on the secretary of state.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: I've been a member of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee; I run for the presidency with full knowledge that his great responsibility, really, given to him by the Constitution and by the force of events, is in the field of foreign affairs.
Speech: I've been a member of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee; I run for the presidency with full knowledge that his great responsibility, really, given to him by the Constitution and by the force of events, is in the field of foreign affairs.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: I'm asking the people's support as president.
Speech: I'm asking the people's support as president.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: We will select the best man we can get.
Speech: We will select the best man we can get.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: But I've not made a judgment, and I have not narrowed down a list of three or four people, among whom would be the candidate.
Speech: But I've not made a judgment, and I have not narrowed down a list of three or four people, among whom would be the candidate.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: NIXON: Well Mr. Edwards, as you probably know, I have consistently answered all questions with regard to who will be in the next cabinet by saying that that is the responsibility of the next president, and it would be inappropriate to make any decisions on that or to announce any prior to the time that I had the right to do so.
Speech: Well Mr. Edwards, as you probably know, I have consistently answered all questions with regard to who will be in the next cabinet by saying that that is the responsibility of the next president, and it would be inappropriate to make any decisions on that or to announce any prior to the time that I had the right to do so.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: So that is my answer to this question.
Speech: So that is my answer to this question.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: If you don't mind, I'd like to use the balance of the time to respond to one of the comments that Senator Kennedy made on the previous question.
Speech: If you don't mind, I'd like to use the balance of the time to respond to one of the comments that Senator Kennedy made on the previous question.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: Eh- He was talking about the Castro regime and what we had been eh- doing in Latin America.
Speech: Eh- He was talking about the Castro regime and what we had been eh- doing in Latin America.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: I would like to point out that when we look at our programs in Latin America, we find that we have appropriated five times as much for Latin America as was appropriated by the previous Administration; we find that we have two billion dollars more for the Export-Import Bank; we have a new bank for Latin America alone of a billion dollars; we have the new program which was submitted at the Bogota Conference - this new program that President Eisenhower submitted, approved by the last Congress - for five hundred million dollars.
Speech: I would like to point out that when we look at our programs in Latin America, we find that we have appropriated five times as much for Latin America as was appropriated by the previous Administration; we find that we have two billion dollars more for the Export-Import Bank; we have a new bank for Latin America alone of a billion dollars; we have the new program which was submitted at the Bogota Conference - this new program that President Eisenhower submitted, approved by the last Congress - for five hundred million dollars.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: We have moved in Latin America very effectively, and I'd also like to point this out: Senator Kennedy complains very appropriately about our inadequate ra- radio broadcasts for Latin America.
Speech: We have moved in Latin America very effectively, and I'd also like to point this out: Senator Kennedy complains very appropriately about our inadequate ra- radio broadcasts for Latin America.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: Let me point out again that his Congress - the Democratic Congress - has cut eighty million dollars off of the Voice of America appropriations.
Speech: Let me point out again that his Congress - the Democratic Congress - has cut eighty million dollars off of the Voice of America appropriations.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: Now, he has to get a better job out of his Congress if he's going to get us the money that we need to conduct the foreign affairs of this country in Latin America or any place else.
Speech: Now, he has to get a better job out of his Congress if he's going to get us the money that we need to conduct the foreign affairs of this country in Latin America or any place else.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: NIXON: Mr. Cronkite, I naturally am aware of it, because I, of course, pay attention to everything Senator Kennedy says, as well as Senator Fulbright.
Speech: Mr. Cronkite, I naturally am aware of it, because I, of course, pay attention to everything Senator Kennedy says, as well as Senator Fulbright.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: Now, in this connection I want to point out that the facts simply aren't as stated.
Speech: Now, in this connection I want to point out that the facts simply aren't as stated.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: First of all, the report to which Senator Kennedy refers is one that was made many, many months ago and related particularly to the uh - period immediately after Sputnik.
Speech: First of all, the report to which Senator Kennedy refers is one that was made many, many months ago and related particularly to the uh - period immediately after Sputnik.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: Second, as far as this report is concerned, I would have no objection to having it made public.
Speech: Second, as far as this report is concerned, I would have no objection to having it made public.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: Third, I would say this with regard to this report, with regard to Gallup Polls of prestige abroad and everything else that we've been hearing about "what about American prestige abroad": America's prestige abroad will be just as high as the spokesmen for America allow it to be.
Speech: Third, I would say this with regard to this report, with regard to Gallup Polls of prestige abroad and everything else that we've been hearing about "what about American prestige abroad": America's prestige abroad will be just as high as the spokesmen for America allow it to be.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: Now, when we have a presidential candidate, for example - Senator Kennedy - stating over and over again that the United States is second in space and the fact of the matter is that the space score today is twenty-eight to eight - we've had twenty-eight successful shots, they've had eight; when he states that we're second in education, and I have seen Soviet education and I've seen ours, and we're not; that we're second in science because they may be ahead in one area or another, when overall we're way ahead of the Soviet Union and all other countries in science; when he says as he did in January of this year that we have the worst slums, that we have the most crowded schools; when he says that seventeen million people go to bed hungry every night; when he makes statements like this, what does this do to American prestige?
Speech: Now, when we have a presidential candidate, for example - Senator Kennedy - stating over and over again that the United States is second in space and the fact of the matter is that the space score today is twenty-eight to eight - we've had twenty-eight successful shots, they've had eight; when he states that we're second in education, and I have seen Soviet education and I've seen ours, and we're not; that we're second in science because they may be ahead in one area or another, when overall we're way ahead of the Soviet Union and all other countries in science; when he says as he did in January of this year that we have the worst slums, that we have the most crowded schools; when he says that seventeen million people go to bed hungry every night; when he makes statements like this, what does this do to American prestige?
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: Well, it can only have the effect certainly of reducing it.
Speech: Well, it can only have the effect certainly of reducing it.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: Well let me make one thing clear.
Speech: Well let me make one thing clear.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: Senator Kennedy has a responsibility to criticize those things that are wrong, but he has also a responsibility to be right in his criticism.
Speech: Senator Kennedy has a responsibility to criticize those things that are wrong, but he has also a responsibility to be right in his criticism.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: Every one of these items that I have mentioned he's been wrong - dead wrong.
Speech: Every one of these items that I have mentioned he's been wrong - dead wrong.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: And for that reason he has contributed to any lack of prestige.
Speech: And for that reason he has contributed to any lack of prestige.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: Finally, let me say this: as far as prestige is concerned, the first place it would show up would be in the United Nations.
Speech: Finally, let me say this: as far as prestige is concerned, the first place it would show up would be in the United Nations.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: Now Senator Kennedy has referred to the vote on Communist China.
Speech: Now Senator Kennedy has referred to the vote on Communist China.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: Let's look at the vote on Hungary.
Speech: Let's look at the vote on Hungary.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: There we got more votes for condemning Hungary and looking into that situation than we got the last year.
Speech: There we got more votes for condemning Hungary and looking into that situation than we got the last year.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: Let's look at the reaction eh - reaction to Khrushchev and Eisenhower at the last U.N. session.
Speech: Let's look at the reaction eh - reaction to Khrushchev and Eisenhower at the last U.N. session.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: Did Khrushchev gain because he took his shoe off and pounded the table and shouted and insulted?
Speech: Did Khrushchev gain because he took his shoe off and pounded the table and shouted and insulted?
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: Not at all.
Speech: Not at all.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: The President gained.
Speech: The President gained.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: America gained by continuing the dignity, the decency that has characterized us and it's that that keeps the prestige of America up, not running down America the way Senator Kennedy has been running her down.
Speech: America gained by continuing the dignity, the decency that has characterized us and it's that that keeps the prestige of America up, not running down America the way Senator Kennedy has been running her down.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: KENNEDY: I really don't need uh - Mr. Nixon to tell me about what my responsibilities are as a citizen.
Speech: I really don't need uh - Mr. Nixon to tell me about what my responsibilities are as a citizen.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: I've served this country for fourteen years in the Congress and before that in the service.
Speech: I've served this country for fourteen years in the Congress and before that in the service.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: I've just as high a devotion, just as high an opinion.
Speech: I've just as high a devotion, just as high an opinion.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: What I downgrade, Mr. Nixon, is the leadership the country is getting, not the country.
Speech: What I downgrade, Mr. Nixon, is the leadership the country is getting, not the country.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: Now I didn't make most of the statements that you said I made.
Speech: Now I didn't make most of the statements that you said I made.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: The s- I believe the Soviet Union is first in outer space.
Speech: The s- I believe the Soviet Union is first in outer space.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: We have - may have made more shots but the size of their rocket thrust and all the rest - you yourself said to Khrushchev, "You may be ahead of us in rocket thrust but we're ahead of you in color television" in your famous discussion in the kitchen.
Speech: We have - may have made more shots but the size of their rocket thrust and all the rest - you yourself said to Khrushchev, "You may be ahead of us in rocket thrust but we're ahead of you in color television" in your famous discussion in the kitchen.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: I think that color television is not as important as rocket thrust.
Speech: I think that color television is not as important as rocket thrust.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: Secondly, I didn't say we had the worst slums in the world.
Speech: Secondly, I didn't say we had the worst slums in the world.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: I said we had too many slums.
Speech: I said we had too many slums.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: And that they are bad, and we ought to do something about them, and we ought to support housing legislation which this Administration has opposed.
Speech: And that they are bad, and we ought to do something about them, and we ought to support housing legislation which this Administration has opposed.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: I didn't say we had the worst education in the world.
Speech: I didn't say we had the worst education in the world.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: What I said was that ten years ago, we were producing twice as many scientists and engineers as the Soviet Union and today they're producing twice as many as we are, and that this affects our security around the world.
Speech: What I said was that ten years ago, we were producing twice as many scientists and engineers as the Soviet Union and today they're producing twice as many as we are, and that this affects our security around the world.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: And fourth, I believe that the polls and other studies and votes in the United Nations and anyone reading the paper and any citizen of the United States must come to the conclusion that the United States no longer carries the same image of a vital society on the move with its brightest days ahead as it carried a decade or two decades ago.
Speech: And fourth, I believe that the polls and other studies and votes in the United Nations and anyone reading the paper and any citizen of the United States must come to the conclusion that the United States no longer carries the same image of a vital society on the move with its brightest days ahead as it carried a decade or two decades ago.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: Part of that is because we've stood still here at home, because we haven't met our problems in the United States, because we haven't had a moving economy.
Speech: Part of that is because we've stood still here at home, because we haven't met our problems in the United States, because we haven't had a moving economy.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: Part of that, as the Gallup Polls show, is because the Soviet Union made a breakthrough in outer space.
Speech: Part of that, as the Gallup Polls show, is because the Soviet Union made a breakthrough in outer space.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: Mr. George Allen, head of your Information Service, has said that that made the people of the world begin to wonder whether we were first in science.
Speech: Mr. George Allen, head of your Information Service, has said that that made the people of the world begin to wonder whether we were first in science.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: We're first in other areas of science but in space, which is the new science, we're not first.
Speech: We're first in other areas of science but in space, which is the new science, we're not first.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: KENNEDY: Yes, I think the next president of the United States should make one last effort to secure an agreement on the cessation of tests, number one.
Speech: Yes, I think the next president of the United States should make one last effort to secure an agreement on the cessation of tests, number one.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: I think we should go back to Geneva, who's ever elected president, Mr. Nixon or myself, and try once again.
Speech: I think we should go back to Geneva, who's ever elected president, Mr. Nixon or myself, and try once again.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: If we fail then, if we're unable to come to an agreement - and I hope we can come to an agreement because it does not merely involve now the United States, Britain, France, and the Soviet Union as atomic powers.
Speech: If we fail then, if we're unable to come to an agreement - and I hope we can come to an agreement because it does not merely involve now the United States, Britain, France, and the Soviet Union as atomic powers.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: Because new breakthroughs in atomic energy technology there's some indications that by the time the next president's term of office has come to an end, there may be ten, fifteen, or twenty countries with an atomic capacity, perhaps that many testing bombs with all the effect that it could have on the atmosphere and with all the chances that more and more countries will have an atomic capacity, with more and more chance of war.
Speech: Because new breakthroughs in atomic energy technology there's some indications that by the time the next president's term of office has come to an end, there may be ten, fifteen, or twenty countries with an atomic capacity, perhaps that many testing bombs with all the effect that it could have on the atmosphere and with all the chances that more and more countries will have an atomic capacity, with more and more chance of war.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: So one more effort should be made.
Speech: So one more effort should be made.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: I don't think that even if that effort fails that it will be necessary to carry on tests in the atmosphere which pollute the atmosphere.
Speech: I don't think that even if that effort fails that it will be necessary to carry on tests in the atmosphere which pollute the atmosphere.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: They can be carried out underground, they c- could be carried on in outer space.
Speech: They can be carried out underground, they c- could be carried on in outer space.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: But I believe the effort should be made once more by who's ever elected president of the United States.
Speech: But I believe the effort should be made once more by who's ever elected president of the United States.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: If we fail, it's been a great serious failure for everyone - for the human race.
Speech: If we fail, it's been a great serious failure for everyone - for the human race.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: I hope we can succeed.
Speech: I hope we can succeed.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: But then if we fail responsibility will be clearly on the Russians and then we'll have to meet our responsibilities to the security of the United States, and there may have to be testing underground.
Speech: But then if we fail responsibility will be clearly on the Russians and then we'll have to meet our responsibilities to the security of the United States, and there may have to be testing underground.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: I think the Atomic Energy Committee is prepared for it.
Speech: I think the Atomic Energy Committee is prepared for it.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: There may be testing in outer space.
Speech: There may be testing in outer space.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: I hope it will not be necessary for any power to resume uh - testing in the atmosphere.
Speech: I hope it will not be necessary for any power to resume uh - testing in the atmosphere.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: It's possible to detect those kind of tests.
Speech: It's possible to detect those kind of tests.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: The kind of tests which you can't detect are underground or in - in uh - perhaps in outer space.
Speech: The kind of tests which you can't detect are underground or in - in uh - perhaps in outer space.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: So that I'm hopeful we can try once more.
Speech: So that I'm hopeful we can try once more.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: If we fail then we must meet our responsibilities to ourselves.
Speech: If we fail then we must meet our responsibilities to ourselves.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: But I'm most concerned about the whole problem of the spread of atomic weapons.
Speech: But I'm most concerned about the whole problem of the spread of atomic weapons.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: China may have it by 1963, Egypt.
Speech: China may have it by 1963, Egypt.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: War has been the constant companion of mankind, so to have these weapons disseminated around the world, I believe means that we're going to move through a period of hazard in the next few years.
Speech: War has been the constant companion of mankind, so to have these weapons disseminated around the world, I believe means that we're going to move through a period of hazard in the next few years.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: We ought to make one last effort.
Speech: We ought to make one last effort.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: NIXON: Yes.
Speech: Yes.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: I would say first of all that we must have in mind the fact that we have been negotiating to get tests inspected and uh - to get an agreement for many, many months.
Speech: I would say first of all that we must have in mind the fact that we have been negotiating to get tests inspected and uh - to get an agreement for many, many months.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: As a matter of fact, there's been a moratorium on testing as a result of the fact that we have been negotiating.
Speech: As a matter of fact, there's been a moratorium on testing as a result of the fact that we have been negotiating.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: I've reached the conclusion that the Soviet Union is actually filibustering.
Speech: I've reached the conclusion that the Soviet Union is actually filibustering.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: I've reached the conclusion, too, based on the reports that have been made, that they may be cheating.
Speech: I've reached the conclusion, too, based on the reports that have been made, that they may be cheating.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: I don't think we can wait until the next president is inaugurated and then uh - select a new team and then all the months of negotiating that will take place before we reach a decision, I think that immediately after this election we should set a timetable - the next president, working with the present President, President Eisenhower - a timetable to break the Soviet filibuster.
Speech: I don't think we can wait until the next president is inaugurated and then uh - select a new team and then all the months of negotiating that will take place before we reach a decision, I think that immediately after this election we should set a timetable - the next president, working with the present President, President Eisenhower - a timetable to break the Soviet filibuster.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: There should be no tests in the atmosphere; that rules out any fall-out.
Speech: There should be no tests in the atmosphere; that rules out any fall-out.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: But as far as underground tests for developing peaceful uses of atomic energy, we should not allow this Soviet filibuster to continue.
Speech: But as far as underground tests for developing peaceful uses of atomic energy, we should not allow this Soviet filibuster to continue.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: I think it's time for them to fish or cut bait.
Speech: I think it's time for them to fish or cut bait.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: I think that the next president immediately after his election should sit down with the President, work out a timetable, and - get a decision on this before January of next year.
Speech: I think that the next president immediately after his election should sit down with the President, work out a timetable, and - get a decision on this before January of next year.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: NIXON: Well the conditions I laid out in one of our previous television debates, and it's rather difficult to be much more specific than that.
Speech: Well the conditions I laid out in one of our previous television debates, and it's rather difficult to be much more specific than that.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: Uh - First of all, we have to have adequate preparation for a summit conference.
Speech: Uh - First of all, we have to have adequate preparation for a summit conference.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: This means at the secretary of state level and at the ambassadorial level.
Speech: This means at the secretary of state level and at the ambassadorial level.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: By adequate preparation I mean that at that level we must prepare an agenda, an agenda agreed upon with the approval of the heads of state involved.
Speech: By adequate preparation I mean that at that level we must prepare an agenda, an agenda agreed upon with the approval of the heads of state involved.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: Now this agenda should delineate those issues on which there is a possibility of some agreement or negotiation.
Speech: Now this agenda should delineate those issues on which there is a possibility of some agreement or negotiation.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: I don't believe we should go to a summit conference unless we have such an agenda, unless we have some reasonable insur- assurance from Mr. Khrushchev that he intends seriously to negotiate on those points.
Speech: I don't believe we should go to a summit conference unless we have such an agenda, unless we have some reasonable insur- assurance from Mr. Khrushchev that he intends seriously to negotiate on those points.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: Now this may seem like a rigid, inflexible position.
Speech: Now this may seem like a rigid, inflexible position.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: But let's look at the other side of the coin.
Speech: But let's look at the other side of the coin.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: If we build up the hopes of the world by having a summit conference that is not adequately prepared, and then, if Mr. Khrushchev finds some excuse for breaking it up - as he did this one - because he isn't going to get his way - we'd set back the cause of peace.
Speech: If we build up the hopes of the world by having a summit conference that is not adequately prepared, and then, if Mr. Khrushchev finds some excuse for breaking it up - as he did this one - because he isn't going to get his way - we'd set back the cause of peace.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: We do not help it.
Speech: We do not help it.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: We can, in other words, negotiate many of these items of difference between us without going to the summit.
Speech: We can, in other words, negotiate many of these items of difference between us without going to the summit.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: I think we have to make a greater effort than we have been making at the secretary of state level, at the ambassadorial level, to work out the differences that we have.
Speech: I think we have to make a greater effort than we have been making at the secretary of state level, at the ambassadorial level, to work out the differences that we have.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: And so far as the summit conference is concerned, it should only be entered in upon, it should only be agreed upon, if the negotiations have reached the point that we have some reasonable assurance that something is going to come out of it, other than some phony spirit - a spirit of Geneva, or Camp David, or whatever it is.
Speech: And so far as the summit conference is concerned, it should only be entered in upon, it should only be agreed upon, if the negotiations have reached the point that we have some reasonable assurance that something is going to come out of it, other than some phony spirit - a spirit of Geneva, or Camp David, or whatever it is.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: When I say "phony spirit," I mean phony, not because the spirit is not good on our side, but because the Soviet Union simply doesn't intend to carry out what they say.
Speech: When I say "phony spirit," I mean phony, not because the spirit is not good on our side, but because the Soviet Union simply doesn't intend to carry out what they say.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: Now, these are the conditions that I can lay out.
Speech: Now, these are the conditions that I can lay out.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: I cannot be more precise than that, because until we see what Mr. Khrushchev does and what he says uh - we cannot indicate what our plans will be.
Speech: I cannot be more precise than that, because until we see what Mr. Khrushchev does and what he says uh - we cannot indicate what our plans will be.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: KENNEDY: Well, I think the president of the United States last winter indicated that before he'd go to the summit in May he did last fall, he indicated that there should be some agenda, that there should be some prior agreement.
Speech: Well, I think the president of the United States last winter indicated that before he'd go to the summit in May he did last fall, he indicated that there should be some agenda, that there should be some prior agreement.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: He hoped that there would be uh - b- be an agreement in part in disarmament.
Speech: He hoped that there would be uh - b- be an agreement in part in disarmament.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: He also expressed the hope that there should be some understanding of the general situation in Berlin.
Speech: He also expressed the hope that there should be some understanding of the general situation in Berlin.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: The Soviet Union refused to agree to that, and we went to the summit and it was disastrous.
Speech: The Soviet Union refused to agree to that, and we went to the summit and it was disastrous.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: I believe we should not go to the summit until there is some reason to believe that a meeting of minds can be obtained on either Berlin, outer space, or general disarmament - including nuclear testing.
Speech: I believe we should not go to the summit until there is some reason to believe that a meeting of minds can be obtained on either Berlin, outer space, or general disarmament - including nuclear testing.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: In addition, I believe the next president in January and February should go to work in building the strength of the United States.
Speech: In addition, I believe the next president in January and February should go to work in building the strength of the United States.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: The Soviet Union does understand strength.
Speech: The Soviet Union does understand strength.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: We arm to parley, Winston Churchill said ten years ago.
Speech: We arm to parley, Winston Churchill said ten years ago.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: If we are strong, particularly as we face a crisis over Berlin - which we may in the spring, or in the winter - it's important that we maintain our determination here; that we indicate that we're building our strength; that we are determined to protect our position; that we're determined to protect our commitment.
Speech: If we are strong, particularly as we face a crisis over Berlin - which we may in the spring, or in the winter - it's important that we maintain our determination here; that we indicate that we're building our strength; that we are determined to protect our position; that we're determined to protect our commitment.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: And then I believe we should indicate our desire to live at peace with the world.
Speech: And then I believe we should indicate our desire to live at peace with the world.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: But until we're strong here, until we're moving here, I believe a summit could not be successful.
Speech: But until we're strong here, until we're moving here, I believe a summit could not be successful.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: I hope that before we do meet, there will be preliminary agreements on those four questions, or at least two of them, or even one of them, which would warrant such a meeting.
Speech: I hope that before we do meet, there will be preliminary agreements on those four questions, or at least two of them, or even one of them, which would warrant such a meeting.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: I think if we had stuck by that position last winter, we would have been in a better position in May.
Speech: I think if we had stuck by that position last winter, we would have been in a better position in May.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: KENNEDY: One of the areas, and of course the most vulnerable area is - I have felt, has been Eastern Europe.
Speech: One of the areas, and of course the most vulnerable area is - I have felt, has been Eastern Europe.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: I've been critical of the Administration's failure to suggest policies which would make it possible for us to establish, for example, closer relations with Poland, particularly after the fifty-five-fifty-six period and the Hungarian revolution.
Speech: I've been critical of the Administration's failure to suggest policies which would make it possible for us to establish, for example, closer relations with Poland, particularly after the fifty-five-fifty-six period and the Hungarian revolution.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: We indicated at that time that we were not going to intervene militarily.
Speech: We indicated at that time that we were not going to intervene militarily.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: But there was a period there when Poland demonstrated a national independence and even the Polish government moved some differn- di- distance away from the Soviet Union.
Speech: But there was a period there when Poland demonstrated a national independence and even the Polish government moved some differn- di- distance away from the Soviet Union.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: I suggested that we amend our legislation so that we could enjoy closer economic ties.
Speech: I suggested that we amend our legislation so that we could enjoy closer economic ties.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: We received the support first of the Administration and then not, and we were defeated by one vote in the Senate.
Speech: We received the support first of the Administration and then not, and we were defeated by one vote in the Senate.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: We passed the bill in the Senate this year but it didn't pass the House.
Speech: We passed the bill in the Senate this year but it didn't pass the House.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: I would say Eastern Europe is the area of vulnerability of the uh - s- of the Soviet Union.
Speech: I would say Eastern Europe is the area of vulnerability of the uh - s- of the Soviet Union.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: Secondly, the relations between Russia and China.
Speech: Secondly, the relations between Russia and China.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: They are now engaged in a debate over whether war is the means of Communizing the world or whether they should use subversion, infiltration, economic struggles and all the rest.
Speech: They are now engaged in a debate over whether war is the means of Communizing the world or whether they should use subversion, infiltration, economic struggles and all the rest.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: No one can say what that course of action will be, but I think the next president of the United States should watch it carefully.
Speech: No one can say what that course of action will be, but I think the next president of the United States should watch it carefully.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: If those two powers should split, it could have great effects throughout the entire world.
Speech: If those two powers should split, it could have great effects throughout the entire world.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: Thirdly, I believe that India represents a great area for affirmative action by the free world.
Speech: Thirdly, I believe that India represents a great area for affirmative action by the free world.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: India started from about the same place that China did.
Speech: India started from about the same place that China did.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: Chinese Communists have been moving ahead the last ten years.
Speech: Chinese Communists have been moving ahead the last ten years.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: India under a free society has been making some progress.
Speech: India under a free society has been making some progress.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: But if India does not succeed - with her four hundred and fifty million people, if she can't make freedom work - then people around the world are going to determine - particularly in the underdeveloped world - that the only way that they can develop their resources is through the Communist system.
Speech: But if India does not succeed - with her four hundred and fifty million people, if she can't make freedom work - then people around the world are going to determine - particularly in the underdeveloped world - that the only way that they can develop their resources is through the Communist system.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: Fourth, let me say that in Africa, Asia, Latin America, Eastern Europe, the great force on our side is the desire of people to be free.
Speech: Fourth, let me say that in Africa, Asia, Latin America, Eastern Europe, the great force on our side is the desire of people to be free.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: This has expressed itself in the revolts in Eastern Europe.
Speech: This has expressed itself in the revolts in Eastern Europe.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: It's expressed itself in the desire of the people of Africa to be independent of Western Europe.
Speech: It's expressed itself in the desire of the people of Africa to be independent of Western Europe.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: They want to be free.
Speech: They want to be free.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: And my judgment is that they don't want to give their freedom up to become Communists.
Speech: And my judgment is that they don't want to give their freedom up to become Communists.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: They want to stay free, independent perhaps of us, but certainly independent of the Communists.
Speech: They want to stay free, independent perhaps of us, but certainly independent of the Communists.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: And I believe if we identify ourselves with that force, if we identify ourselves with it as Lincoln, as Wilson did, as Franklin Roosevelt did, if we become known as the friend of freedom, sustaining freedom, helping freedom, helping these people in the fight against poverty and ignorance and disease, helping them build their lives, I believe in Latin America, Africa, and Asia, eventually in the Eastern Europe and the Middle East, certainly in Western Europe, we can strengthen freedom.
Speech: And I believe if we identify ourselves with that force, if we identify ourselves with it as Lincoln, as Wilson did, as Franklin Roosevelt did, if we become known as the friend of freedom, sustaining freedom, helping freedom, helping these people in the fight against poverty and ignorance and disease, helping them build their lives, I believe in Latin America, Africa, and Asia, eventually in the Eastern Europe and the Middle East, certainly in Western Europe, we can strengthen freedom.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Speech: We can make it move.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: We can put the Communists on the defensive.
Speech: We can put the Communists on the defensive.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: NIXON: First, with regard to Poland, when I talked to Mr. Gomulka, the present leader of Poland, for six hours in Warsaw last year, I learned something about their problems and particularly his.
Speech: First, with regard to Poland, when I talked to Mr. Gomulka, the present leader of Poland, for six hours in Warsaw last year, I learned something about their problems and particularly his.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: Right under the Soviet gun, with Soviet troops there, he is in a very difficult position in taking anything independent, a position which would be independent of the Soviet Union.
Speech: Right under the Soviet gun, with Soviet troops there, he is in a very difficult position in taking anything independent, a position which would be independent of the Soviet Union.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: And yet let's just see what we've done for Poland, A half a billion dollars worth of aid has gone to Poland, primarily economic, primarily to go to the people of Poland.
Speech: And yet let's just see what we've done for Poland, A half a billion dollars worth of aid has gone to Poland, primarily economic, primarily to go to the people of Poland.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: This should continue and it can be stepped up to give them hope and to keep alive the hope for freedom that I can testify they have so deeply within them.
Speech: This should continue and it can be stepped up to give them hope and to keep alive the hope for freedom that I can testify they have so deeply within them.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: In addition we can have more exchange with Poland or with any other of the Iron Curtain countries which show some desire to take a different path than the path that has been taken by the ones that are complete satellites of the Soviet Union.
Speech: In addition we can have more exchange with Poland or with any other of the Iron Curtain countries which show some desire to take a different path than the path that has been taken by the ones that are complete satellites of the Soviet Union.

Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: Now as far as the balance of the world is concerned, I of course don't have as much time as Senator Kennedy had.
Speech: Now as far as the balance of the world is concerned, I of course don't have as much time as Senator Kennedy had.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: I would just like to s- add this one point.
Speech: I would just like to s- add this one point.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: If we are going to have the initiative in the world, we must remember that the people of Africa and Asia and Latin America don't want to be pawns simply in a struggle between two great powers - the Soviet Union and the United States.
Speech: If we are going to have the initiative in the world, we must remember that the people of Africa and Asia and Latin America don't want to be pawns simply in a struggle between two great powers - the Soviet Union and the United States.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: We have to let them know that we want to help them, not because we're simply trying to save our own skins, not because we're simply trying to fight Communism; but because we care for them, because we stand for freedom, because if there were no Communism in the world, we would still fight poverty and misery and disease and tyranny.
Speech: We have to let them know that we want to help them, not because we're simply trying to save our own skins, not because we're simply trying to fight Communism; but because we care for them, because we stand for freedom, because if there were no Communism in the world, we would still fight poverty and misery and disease and tyranny.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: If we can get that across to the people of these countries, in this decade of the sixties, the struggle for freedom will be won.
Speech: If we can get that across to the people of these countries, in this decade of the sixties, the struggle for freedom will be won.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: NIXON: I would say that the issue will stay with us as a campaign issue just as long as Senator Kennedy persists in what I think is a fundamental error.
Speech: I would say that the issue will stay with us as a campaign issue just as long as Senator Kennedy persists in what I think is a fundamental error.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: He says he supports the President's position.
Speech: He says he supports the President's position.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: He says that he voted for the resolution.
Speech: He says that he voted for the resolution.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: Well just let me point this out; he voted for the resolution in 1955 which gave the president the power to use the forces of the United States to defend Formosa and the offshore islands.
Speech: Well just let me point this out; he voted for the resolution in 1955 which gave the president the power to use the forces of the United States to defend Formosa and the offshore islands.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: But he also voted then for an amendment - which was lost, fortunately - an amendment which would have drawn a line and left out those islands and denied the p- right to the president to defend those islands if he thought that it was an attack on Formosa.
Speech: But he also voted then for an amendment - which was lost, fortunately - an amendment which would have drawn a line and left out those islands and denied the p- right to the president to defend those islands if he thought that it was an attack on Formosa.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: He repeated that error in 1959, in the speech that he made.
Speech: He repeated that error in 1959, in the speech that he made.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: He repeated it again in a television debate that we had.
Speech: He repeated it again in a television debate that we had.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: Now, my point is this: Senator Kennedy has got to be consistent here.
Speech: Now, my point is this: Senator Kennedy has got to be consistent here.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: Either he's for the President and he's against the position that those who opposed the President in fifty-five and fifty-nine - and the Senator's position itself, stated the other day in our debate - either he is for the President and against that position or we simply have a disagreement here that must continue to be debated.
Speech: Either he's for the President and he's against the position that those who opposed the President in fifty-five and fifty-nine - and the Senator's position itself, stated the other day in our debate - either he is for the President and against that position or we simply have a disagreement here that must continue to be debated.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: Now if the Senator in his answer to this question will say "I now will depart, or retract my previous views; I think I was wrong in I 955; I think I was wrong in 1959; and I think I was wrong in our television debate to say that we should draw a line leaving out Quemoy and Matsu - draw a line in effect abandoning these islands to the Communists;" then this will be right out of the campaign because there will be no issue between us.
Speech: Now if the Senator in his answer to this question will say "I now will depart, or retract my previous views; I think I was wrong in I 955; I think I was wrong in 1959; and I think I was wrong in our television debate to say that we should draw a line leaving out Quemoy and Matsu - draw a line in effect abandoning these islands to the Communists;" then this will be right out of the campaign because there will be no issue between us.

Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: I support the President's position.
Speech: I support the President's position.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: I have always opposed drawing a line.
Speech: I have always opposed drawing a line.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: I have opposed drawing a line because I know that the moment you draw a line, that is an encouragement for the Communists to attack - to step up their blackmail and to force you into the war that none of us want.
Speech: I have opposed drawing a line because I know that the moment you draw a line, that is an encouragement for the Communists to attack - to step up their blackmail and to force you into the war that none of us want.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: And so I would hope that Senator Kennedy in his answer today would clear it up.
Speech: And so I would hope that Senator Kennedy in his answer today would clear it up.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: It isn't enough for him to say "I support the President's position, that I voted for the resolution."
Speech: It isn't enough for him to say "I support the President's position, that I voted for the resolution."
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: Of course, he voted for the resolution - it was virtually unanimous.
Speech: Of course, he voted for the resolution - it was virtually unanimous.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: But the point is, what about his error in voting for the amendment, which was not adopted, and then persisting in it in fifty-nine, persisting in it in the debate.
Speech: But the point is, what about his error in voting for the amendment, which was not adopted, and then persisting in it in fifty-nine, persisting in it in the debate.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: It's very simple for him to clear it up.
Speech: It's very simple for him to clear it up.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: He can say now that he no longer believes that a line should be drawn leaving these islands out of the perimeter of defense.
Speech: He can say now that he no longer believes that a line should be drawn leaving these islands out of the perimeter of defense.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: If he says that, this issue will not be discussed in the campaign.
Speech: If he says that, this issue will not be discussed in the campaign.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: KENNEDY: Well, Mr. Nixon, to go back to 1955.
Speech: Well, Mr. Nixon, to go back to 1955.

Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: The resolution commits the president in the United States, which I supported, to defend uh - Formosa, the Pescadores, and if it was his military judgment, these islands.
Speech: The resolution commits the president in the United States, which I supported, to defend uh - Formosa, the Pescadores, and if it was his military judgment, these islands.

Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: Then the President sent a mission, composed of Admiral Radford and Mr. Robertson, to persuade Chiang Kai-shek in the spring of fifty-five to withdraw from the two islands, because they were exposed.
Speech: Then the President sent a mission, composed of Admiral Radford and Mr. Robertson, to persuade Chiang Kai-shek in the spring of fifty-five to withdraw from the two islands, because they were exposed.

Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: The President was unsuccessful; Chiang Kai-shek would not withdraw.
Speech: The President was unsuccessful; Chiang Kai-shek would not withdraw.

Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: I refer to the fact that in 1958, as a member of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, I'm very familiar with the position that the United States took in negotiating with the Chinese Communists on these two islands.
Speech: I refer to the fact that in 1958, as a member of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, I'm very familiar with the position that the United States took in negotiating with the Chinese Communists on these two islands.

Name: John F. Kennedy

Speech: General Twining, in January, fifty-nine, described the position of the United States.

Name: John F. Kennedy

Speech: The position of the United States has been that this build-up, in the words of the president, has been foolish.

Name: John F. Kennedy

Name: John F. Kennedy

Speech: Because he will not withdraw, because he's committed to these islands, because we've been unable to persuade him to withdraw, we are in a very difficult position.

Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: And therefore, the President's judgment has been that we should defend the islands if, in his military judgment and the judgment of the commander in the field, the attack on these islands should be part of an overall attack on Formosa.
Speech: And therefore, the President's judgment has been that we should defend the islands if, in his military judgment and the judgment of the commander in the field, the attack on these islands should be part of an overall attack on Formosa.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Speech: I support that.

Name: John F. Kennedy

Speech: In view of the difficulties we've had with the islands, in view of the difficulties and disputes we've had with Chiang Kai-shek, that's the only position we can take.

Name: John F. Kennedy

Speech: That's not the position you took, however.

Name: John F. Kennedy

Speech: The first position you took, when this matter first came up, was that we should draw the line and commit ourselves, as a matter of principle, to defend these islands.

Name: John F. Kennedy

Speech: Not as part of the defense of Formosa and the Pescadores.

Speech: You showed no recognition of the Administration program to try to persuade Chiang Kai-shek for the last five years to withdraw from the islands.

Name: John F. Kennedy

Speech: And I challenge you tonight to deny that the Administration has sent at least several missions to persuade Chiang Kai-shek's withdrawal from these islands.

Name: John F. Kennedy

Speech: And that's the testimony of uh - General Twining and the Assistant Secretary of State in fifty-eight.

Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: KENNEDY: I uh - said that I've served this country for fourteen years.
Speech: I uh - said that I've served this country for fourteen years.

Name: John F. Kennedy

Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: If I lose this election, I will continue in the Senate to try to build a stronger country.
Speech: If I lose this election, I will continue in the Senate to try to build a stronger country.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: But I run because I believe this year the United States has a great opportunity to make a move forward, to make a determination here at home and around the world, that it's going to reestablish itself as a vigorous society.
Speech: But I run because I believe this year the United States has a great opportunity to make a move forward, to make a determination here at home and around the world, that it's going to reestablish itself as a vigorous society.

Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: My judgment is that the Republican party has stood still here in the United States, and it's also stood still around the world.
Speech: My judgment is that the Republican party has stood still here in the United States, and it's also stood still around the world.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: Uh - We're using about fifty percent of our steel capacity today.
Speech: Uh - We're using about fifty percent of our steel capacity today.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Speech: We had a recession in fifty-eight.

Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: We had a recession in fifty-four.
Speech: We had a recession in fifty-four.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: We're not moving ahead in education the way we should.
Speech: We're not moving ahead in education the way we should.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: We didn't make a judgment in fifty-seven and fifty-six and fifty-five and fifty-four that outer space would be important.
Speech: We didn't make a judgment in fifty-seven and fifty-six and fifty-five and fifty-four that outer space would be important.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: If we stand still here, if we appoint people to ambassadorships and positions in Washington who have a status quo outlook, who don't recognize that this is a revolutionary time, then the United States does not maintain its influence.
Speech: If we stand still here, if we appoint people to ambassadorships and positions in Washington who have a status quo outlook, who don't recognize that this is a revolutionary time, then the United States does not maintain its influence.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: And if we fail, the cause of freedom fails.
Speech: And if we fail, the cause of freedom fails.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: I believe it incumbent upon the next president of the United States to get this country moving again, to get our economy moving ahead, to set before the American people its goals, its unfinished business.
Speech: I believe it incumbent upon the next president of the United States to get this country moving again, to get our economy moving ahead, to set before the American people its goals, its unfinished business.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: And then throughout the world appoint the best people we can get, ambassadors who can speak the language - no mere - not merely people who made a political contribution but who can speak the language.

Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Speech: Bring students here; let them see what kind of a country we have.

Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: Mr. Nixon said that we should not regard them as pawns in the cold war; we should identify ourselves with them.

Name: John F. Kennedy

Speech: If that were true, why didn't we identify ourselves with the people of Africa?
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Speech: Why didn't we bring students over here?

Name: John F. Kennedy

Speech: Why did we suddenly offer Congo three hundred students last June when they had the tremendous revolt?

Name: John F. Kennedy

Speech: That was more than we had offered to all of Africa before from the federal government.

Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: I believe that this party - Republican party - has stood still really for twenty-five years - its leadership has.
Speech: I believe that this party - Republican party - has stood still really for twenty-five years - its leadership has.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: It opposed all of the programs of President Roosevelt and others - the minimum wage and for housing and economic growth and development of our natural resources, the Tennessee Valley and all the rest.
Speech: It opposed all of the programs of President Roosevelt and others - the minimum wage and for housing and economic growth and development of our natural resources, the Tennessee Valley and all the rest.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: And I believe that if we can get a party which believes in movement, which believes in going ahead, then we can reestablish our position in the world - strong defense, strong in economic growth, justice for our people, co- guarantee of constitutional rights, so that people will believe that we practice what we preach, and then around the world, particularly to try to reestablish the atmosphere which existed in Latin America at the time of Franklin Roosevelt.
Speech: And I believe that if we can get a party which believes in movement, which believes in going ahead, then we can reestablish our position in the world - strong defense, strong in economic growth, justice for our people, co- guarantee of constitutional rights, so that people will believe that we practice what we preach, and then around the world, particularly to try to reestablish the atmosphere which existed in Latin America at the time of Franklin Roosevelt.

Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: He was a good neighbor in Latin America because he was a good neighbor in the United States; because they saw us as a society that was compassionate, that cared about people, that was moving this country ahead.

Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: I believe it my responsibility as the leader of the Democratic party in 1960 to try to warn the American people that in this crucial time we can no longer afford to stand still.
Speech: I believe it my responsibility as the leader of the Democratic party in 1960 to try to warn the American people that in this crucial time we can no longer afford to stand still.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Speech: We can no longer afford to be second best.

Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: I want people all over the world to look to the United States again, to feel that we're on the move, to feel that our high noon is in the future.

Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: I want Mr. Khrushchev to know that a new generation of Americans who fought in Europe and Italy and the Pacific for freedom in World War II have now taken over in the United States, and that they're going to put this country back to work again.
Speech: I want Mr. Khrushchev to know that a new generation of Americans who fought in Europe and Italy and the Pacific for freedom in World War II have now taken over in the United States, and that they're going to put this country back to work again.

Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: I don't believe that there is anything this country cannot do.
Speech: I don't believe that there is anything this country cannot do.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: I don't believe there's any burden, or any responsibility, that any American would not assume to protect his country, to protect our security, to advance the cause of freedom.
Speech: I don't believe there's any burden, or any responsibility, that any American would not assume to protect his country, to protect our security, to advance the cause of freedom.
Speaker: KENNEDY
Name: John F. Kennedy

Speech: And I believe it incumbent upon us now to do that.

Name: John F. Kennedy

Speech: Franklin Roosevelt said in 1936 that that generation of Americans had a rendezvous with destiny.

Name: John F. Kennedy

Speech: I believe in 1960 and sixty-one and two and three we have a rendezvous with destiny.

Name: John F. Kennedy

Text: And I believe it incumbent upon us to be the defenders of the United States and the defenders of freedom; and to do that, we must give this country leadership and we must get America moving again.
Speech: And I believe it incumbent upon us to be the defenders of the United States and the defenders of freedom; and to do that, we must give this country leadership and we must get America moving again.

Name: John F. Kennedy

Name: Richard M. Nixon

Speech: But America cannot stand pat.

Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: We can't stand pat for the reason that we're in a race, as I've indicated.
Speech: We can't stand pat for the reason that we're in a race, as I've indicated.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: We can't stand pat because it is essential with the conflict that we have around the world that we not just hold our own, that we not keep just freedom for ourselves.
Speech: We can't stand pat because it is essential with the conflict that we have around the world that we not just hold our own, that we not keep just freedom for ourselves.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: It is essential that we extend freedom, extend it to all the world.
Speech: It is essential that we extend freedom, extend it to all the world.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: And this means more than what we've been doing.
Speech: And this means more than what we've been doing.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: It means keeping America even stronger militarily than she is.
Speech: It means keeping America even stronger militarily than she is.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: It means seeing that our economy moves forward even faster than it has.
Speech: It means seeing that our economy moves forward even faster than it has.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: It means making more progress in civil rights than we have so that we can be a splendid example for all the world to see - a democracy in action at its best.
Speech: It means making more progress in civil rights than we have so that we can be a splendid example for all the world to see - a democracy in action at its best.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: Now, looking at the other parts of the world - South America - talking about our record and the previous one.
Speech: Now, looking at the other parts of the world - South America - talking about our record and the previous one.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: We had a good neighbor policy, yes.
Speech: We had a good neighbor policy, yes.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: It sounded fine.
Speech: It sounded fine.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: But let's look at it.
Speech: But let's look at it.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: There were eleven dictators when we came into power in 1953 in Latin America.
Speech: There were eleven dictators when we came into power in 1953 in Latin America.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: There are only three left.
Speech: There are only three left.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: Let's look at Africa.
Speech: Let's look at Africa.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: Twenty new countries in Africa during the course of this Administration.
Speech: Twenty new countries in Africa during the course of this Administration.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: Not one of them selected a Communist government.
Speech: Not one of them selected a Communist government.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: All of them voted for freedom - a free type of government.
Speech: All of them voted for freedom - a free type of government.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: Does this show that Communism has the bigger pull, or freedom has the bigger pull?
Speech: Does this show that Communism has the bigger pull, or freedom has the bigger pull?
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: Am I trying to indicate that we have no problems in Africa or Latin America or Asia?
Speech: Am I trying to indicate that we have no problems in Africa or Latin America or Asia?
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: Of course not.
Speech: Of course not.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: What I am trying to indicate is that the tide of history's on our side, and that we can keep it on our side, because we're on the right side.
Speech: What I am trying to indicate is that the tide of history's on our side, and that we can keep it on our side, because we're on the right side.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: We're on the side of freedom.
Speech: We're on the side of freedom.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: We're on the side of justice against the forces of slavery, against the forces of injustice.
Speech: We're on the side of justice against the forces of slavery, against the forces of injustice.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: But we aren't going to move America forward and we aren't going to be able to lead the world to win this struggle for freedom if we have a permanent inferiority complex about American achievements.
Speech: But we aren't going to move America forward and we aren't going to be able to lead the world to win this struggle for freedom if we have a permanent inferiority complex about American achievements.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: Because we are first in the world in space, as I've indicated; we are first in science; we are first in education, and we're going to move even further ahead with the kind of leadership that we can provide in these years ahead.
Speech: Because we are first in the world in space, as I've indicated; we are first in science; we are first in education, and we're going to move even further ahead with the kind of leadership that we can provide in these years ahead.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: One other point I would make: what could you do?
Speech: One other point I would make: what could you do?
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: Senator Kennedy and I are candidates for the presidency of the United States.
Speech: Senator Kennedy and I are candidates for the presidency of the United States.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: And in the years to come it will be written that one or the other of us was elected and that he was or was not a great president.
Speech: And in the years to come it will be written that one or the other of us was elected and that he was or was not a great president.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: What will determine whether Senator Kennedy or I, if I am elected, was a great president?
Speech: What will determine whether Senator Kennedy or I, if I am elected, was a great president?
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: It will not be our ambition that will determine it, because greatness is not something that is written on a campaign poster.
Speech: It will not be our ambition that will determine it, because greatness is not something that is written on a campaign poster.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: It will be determined to the extent that we represent the deepest ideals, the highest feelings and faith of the American people.
Speech: It will be determined to the extent that we represent the deepest ideals, the highest feelings and faith of the American people.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: In other words, the next president, as he leads America and the free world, can be only as great as the American people are great.
Speech: In other words, the next president, as he leads America and the free world, can be only as great as the American people are great.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: And so I say in conclusion, keep America's faith strong.
Speech: And so I say in conclusion, keep America's faith strong.
Speaker: NIXON
Name: Richard M. Nixon

Text: See that the young people of America, particularly, have faith in the ideals of freedom and faith in God, which distinguishes us from the atheistic materialists who oppose us.
Speech: See that the young people of America, particularly, have faith in the ideals of freedom and faith in God, which distinguishes us from the atheistic materialists who oppose us.
